          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/lotr/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="0" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width=100% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_01.gif" width=6 height=6></td><td width=100% background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_02.gif"></td>
<td width=1><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_03.gif" width=6 height=6></td></tr>
<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Feeding The Swarm<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.67)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9309'>Jeff "Wolfboy" Cox</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9309&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> May 19, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> The movie scene right before the Balrog shows up is a classic with hundreds of Goblins about to overwhelm the Fellowship.  Individually they are weak, but Goblins don’t fight with fair odds.  I’ve seen several different swarm ideas and have enjoyed playing a few of them.  In most of the decks I find that the cards can be divided into four categories:  Core, Recycling, Beef, and Fluff.  From my play experience I find that an 80 card deck is about right for swarms.  Yes, the swarm can dominate and kill around site 5, but I’ve also run out of cards at site 9 and wished for just 2 or 3 more.  To make the comparisons between swarm styles simple I’ll stick with 40 cards for each of them.  Below are three different deck types for swarms.  I know that there are nearly endless possibilities but I picked the three that I’ve personally seen or used myself so don’t get upset if yours isn’t here.<br>
<br>
Core Units<br>
4 × Goblin Runner<br>
4 × Moria Scout<br>
4 × Goblin Scavenger<br>
4 × Goblin Scimitar<br>
4 × Goblin Armory<br>
<br>
The core units are self explanatory and are found in every swarm deck.  I used to think the Scout wasn’t that good, but the 2 vitality and “free with Elf” ability finally convinced me.  Note that it doesn’t have to be an Elf companion, just an Elf.  The Runner is a given.  Scavengers, Scimitars, and Armories are the fuel for the engine that powers the swarm.  The Armories are also key for their prevention of wounds at just the right moment.<br>
<br>
Recycling is important, but don’t go overboard.  Before any of these cards can work, an Orc or weapon must first be in the discard pile or already in play (that’s why it’s called recycling…).  The beauty of conditions like They Are Coming and Goblin Swarms is that they can be played right way and don’t clog your hand.  About the only thing worse than drawing several Host of Thousands in the opening hand is drawing the Balrog.  Don’t be afraid to discard a Host and draw up something useful on the first turn.<br>
<br>
The beef cards provide quite a strength boost to the deck and can be seen as two or three small goblins lumped into one card.  The deck shouldn’t have too many of these because only one or two will actually make it into play at one time.  If Goblin Swarms is working and your beef cards are Orcs, then these should be available every turn.<br>
<br>
The fluff section is where the decks become unique and are built for certain styles of play.  Balrog weapons, Nazgul, Relentless and other surprise cards fit into this category.  I’ve even seen Tentacles but won’t go there…<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Laugh All You Want, We’ll Make More (17 Rares)<br>
<br>
Core Units  (20)<br>
20 × see above<br>
<br>
Recycling  (7)<br>
2 × They Are Coming<br>
3 × Host of Thousands<br>
2 × Goblin Swarm<br>
<br>
Once the deck gets rolling I try to put as many Runners and Scouts on Goblin Swarm as possible.  These two are the heart of the swarm that should see repeated play as much as possible.  Scavengers are great there as well, but make sure you have enough weapons in the discard pile to match their numbers if deciding between a Scout or Scavenger.<br>
<br>
Beef (7)<br>
1 × Flaming Balrog<br>
3 × Cave Troll<br>
2 × Troll’s Keyward<br>
1 × Guard Commander<br>
<br>
Even without the bonus to the Troll, the Keyward is a solid minion because of his 3 vitality for only 3 twilight.  The Guard Commander is nice to have around for those occasions when you have 10+ twilight left in the pool with no way to spend it.  The Troll and Balrog are great for their damage +1 and fierce attacks.  Nothing like a Runner and Troll at site 2 to stop an early double move.  13 is the magic number!<br>
<br>
Fluff (6)<br>
1 × Goblin Scrabbler<br>
1 × Goblin Warrior<br>
2 × Moria Axe<br>
2 × Tower Assassin<br>
<br>
In my area allies are everywhere.  Elf allies with Secret Sentinels, Hobbits with healing allies, Gandalf with Dreary and Butterbur, Thrarin for Balrog support…  most every deck has them.  Galadriel with her Mirror is even making a comeback.  Moria just doesn’t have much in the way of ally removal.  The Tower Assassin is the easiest one shot that can kill up to two allies.  Sure, he’s roaming forever, but what else are you going to play without needing multiple cards?  Twilight Attea?  I get a lot of smirks for playing the Scrabbler and the Warrior, but they are there to disrupt Shoulder to Shoulder decks.  The Moria Axes are there to add two more weapons to the deck for the Goblin Armories and Scavengers to work with.  I almost added the Spear since the Troll and Balrog can use them, but the Scavengers can only put weapons on Orcs. Plus the axe bonuses are just too sweet.<br>
<br>
Sites to consider:<br>
Mithril Mine, for the weapon recycling and underground<br>
Dimrill Dale, obvious<br>
Anduin Wilderland, no archery is a good thing<br>
Shores of Nen Hithoel, spotting 5 should not be a problem<br>
Summit of Amon Hen, extra cards<br>
<br>
<br>
I Got Your Archery Right Here! (8 Rares) <br>
<br>
Core Units  (18)<br>
20 × see above<br>
 -2 × Goblin Scavenger<br>
<br>
Although the Scavengers are part of the engine, they are not that critical here.  This deck type can win by doing the normal swarm, but the Goblin Armories are best used when someone tries to kill a Marksman or Bowman with aimed archery.  Keeping them alive until they can fire in normal archery will get an extra wound from them.<br>
<br>
Recycling  (8)<br>
3 × They Are Coming<br>
4 × Host of Thousands<br>
1 × Goblin Swarm<br>
<br>
An archery deck will load up the Fellowship with wounds, but will win fewer skirmishes.  The recycling should focus more on getting things out of the discard pile and can’t rely on Goblin Swarms.  Still, one Swarms is about right to support the core units once they get going. <br>
Beef (6)<br>
1 × Flaming Balrog<br>
3 × Moria Archer Troop<br>
2 × Archer Commander<br>
<br>
The Archer Troops look expensive but they aren’t meant to stand alone.  The “archery +1” is a great ability and their 3 vitality makes them worth the cost for their staying power.  The Commander adds some flavor to the swarm and gives the poor Bowman a chance.  The Balrog… well, keep them honest if they don’t have Rare Boromir with Armor out yet.<br>
<br>
Fluff (8)<br>
4 × Goblin Bowman<br>
4 × Goblin Marksman<br>
<br>
Although in the Fluff category, these are the heart of the deck and make it stand apart from the other swarms.  The Bowman doesn’t get much respect with only 4 strength, but he almost always does one wound, which is more than most Goblins can do by themselves.<br>
<br>
Sites to consider:<br>
Great Chasm, obvious<br>
Dimrill Dale, obvious<br>
Anduin Confluence, something to deal with allies<br>
Brown Lands, key site for archers<br>
Summit of Amon Hen, extra cards<br>
<br>
<br>
Where’s The Beef? (6 Rares)<br>
<br>
Core Units  (20)<br>
20 × see above<br>
<br>
The object of this deck is to minimize the number of rare cards so that a beginner player can feel the power of the swarm.  Naturally the deck would benefit from just one Flaming Balrog, Cave Troll, or Keyward, but these are not so important that the deck can’t win without them.<br>
<br>
Recycling  (8)<br>
2 × They Are Coming<br>
4 × Host of Thousands<br>
2 × Goblin Swarms<br>
<br>
This is a standard recycling mix but the deck can survive without the rare Goblin Swarms.  I say focus on getting Goblin Armories, then Swarms, then the big guys.<br>
<br>
Beef (7)<br>
1 × Solo Balrog<br>
3 × Goblin Patrol Troop<br>
3 × Goblin Flankers<br>
<br>
How can you call these beef?  Well, these guys don’t get the glory of their larger kin, but are actually more effective in some areas.  They are Orcs so all the recycling cards will work, the Scavengers can give them weapons, and the Armories can prevent wounds.  The Solo Balrog is more than a “just in case” addition.  If the opponent is moving from site 4 to 5 I’d recommend tossing either 3 or 6 Fellowship cards to They Are Coming to put a few Runners out and then go get the Balrog.  Sure the Runners leave, but now the Balrog was cheaper and you get 3 or 6 new cards.  The bluff is that while the Balrog is discarded if they double move, lots of twilight is leftover, site 6 gives 2 more twilight, and 3 or 6 new cards are drawn that they can’t see with Sting or Glamdring.  Fear of the unknown is a powerful thing and unless loaded up, not many opponents will push.<br>
<br>
Fluff (5)<br>
1 × Relentless<br>
2 × Goblin Wallcrawler<br>
2 × Goblin Spear<br>
<br>
The Spears are added for the same reason that the Moria Axe was added to the first deck.  The Wallcrawlers can easily be swapped for any cheap Orc and the Relentless can be a game winner, but not many are needed in the deck.  Ulaire Nertea and Enquea can help against big Fellowships.  Booster cards can also be used here for their surprise effect.  <br>
<br>
Sites to consider:<br>
Mithril Mine, for the weapon recycling<br>
Dimrill Dale, obvious<br>
Shores of Nen Hithoel, spotting 5 should not be a problem<br>
Summit of Amon Hen, extra cards<br>
<br>
Now of course this is just half of the deck and many Fellowship styles do not fit well.  Swarm decks move fast and can play 6 to 8 cards per turn.  The Fellowship side should try and keep up and a slow developing combo deck won’t work.  Luckily They Are Coming can help with Fellowship clogged hands if those cards can afford to be discarded.  Most of the time I win by overwhelming Frodo, but have to run occasionally so I just can’t move once a turn and hope for the best.  I’ll try to post a complete deck soon once I get a few bugs worked out of the Fellowship side.<br>
<br>
No Relics of Moria?  No Plundered Armories?  These are good, don’t get me wrong, but with They Are Coming, Goblin Armory, and Goblin Swarms on the board, I don’t want to be too reliant upon conditions.  Gandalf with Dreary and Sleep is bad enough as is!<br>
<br>
No Ancient Chieftain?  I don’t play with this guy because while stronger (sometimes much stronger) than the Troll’s Keyward, he only has 2 vitality.  Just begging for aimed archers to blast him.<br>
<br>
No Threat of the Unknown?  I don’t like wounding my own guys and there are only a few in the deck that can be exerted anyway.  Plus it is only getting one card ahead so I’m not sold on it.<br>
<br>
No Tentacles?  Doh!<br>
